Quick Reference

Syntax
What It Does

const [a, b] = arr
Extract by position from an array

const [a, , c] = arr
Skip index 1, take index 0 and 2

const [a, ...rest] = arr
Take first, collect the rest

const { x, y } = obj
Extract named properties from an object

const { x: newName } = obj
Extract and rename x to newName

const { x = 5 } = obj
Extract with a fallback default

const { x: n = 5 } = obj
Rename and set a default

const { a: { b } } = obj
Nested destructuring

function f({ x, y }) {}
Destructure in function parameters

[a, b] = [b, a]
Swap two variables

Key Takeaways

вЂў Destructuring extracts values from arrays and objects into named variables

вЂў Arrays are destructured by position using []; objects are destructured by name using {}

вЂў Use , to skip positions in array destructuring

вЂў Use : to rename a property while destructuring an object

вЂў Use = to set default values when a property might be absent

вЂў Destructuring works in function parameters, for...of loops, and nested structures

вЂў Defaults only activate for undefined вЂ” not for null, 0, or ""

What's Next?

With destructuring under your belt, these topics will click much faster:

вЂў
Spread and rest operators (...) вЂ” the sibling syntax that complements destructuring

вЂў
ES6 modules (import/export) вЂ” which use object destructuring syntax to import named exports

вЂў
React props вЂ” nearly every React component destructures its props in the paramete
